(50659, 22581, NULL, 'Global/Aircraft', 'aircraft_types.csv', '{"Aircraft_Type": "", "Bibliography": "Airliners.net", "Category": "2P", "Common_Name": "C-46 Commando", "Country_Origin": "", "Data_Source": "merged", "Date_Added": "2026-05-23", "Date_Modified": "2026-05-23", "Development_Story": "The Curtiss Commando came into widespread civilian service as both an airliner and a freighter after a large number were built as transports for the US military during World War 2, although the original Curtiss design was intended as an airliner. <p>Originally intended as a competitor to the highly successful Douglas DC-3, which was the preeminent airliner of the time, the Curtiss CW20 was designed to operate on routes of up to 1000km (540nm), which at the time accounted for 90% of the US domestic airline system. The CW-20 featured two 1270kW (1700hp) Wright R2600 Twin Cyclone radial engines, twin vertical tails and a pressurised double lobe, or `double bubble'' fuselage. Accommodation would have been for 36 passengers plus four crew. <p>Later in timing than the DC-3, the CW20 first flew on March 26 1940. In July that year an impressed US Army Air Force ordered 20 unpressurised CW20s, which it named the C46 Commando. The first production aircraft was completed in May 1942, by which time the powerplant choice had been switched to P&W R2800s, and the first deliveries to the US Army occurred that July. <p>Initially the C46 was troubled with reliability problems in military service, but these were soon overcome and the Commando proved to be a useful transport with its relatively cavernous freight hold. <p>A proposed postwar commercial version was the CW20E, but it failed to attract customer interest and thus all Commandos to enter civilian service were ex military aircraft. Most were purchased by American operators for freight work. One postwar version though was the Riddles Airlines C46R which had more powerful engines and better performance. Thirty or so were converted. <p>In late 1998 five Commandos were believed to be operational in Alaska, four in Canada, and as many as seven in Bolivia. <p>", "Dimensions": "Wing span 32.92m (108ft 0in), length 23.27m (76ft 4in), height 6.60m (21ft 8in). Wing area 126.2m2 (1358sq ft).", "Engine_Count": "", "Engine_Type": "", "First_Flight_Year": "", "Full_Designation": "Curtiss C-46 Commando", "Generation": "", "Height_m": "", "IATA_Code": "CWC", "ICAO_Code": "C46", "Length_m": "", "MTOW_kg": "", "Manufacturer": "Curtiss", "Max_Pax": "", "Max_Speed_kmh": "", "Mission_Type": "Passenger", "Model": "C-46 Commando", "Name": "Curtiss C46 Commando", "Origin": "United States of America", "Performance": "C46 - Typical cruising speed 300km/h (162kt). Range with 2585kg (5700lb) payload 1880km (1017nm). C46R - Max speed 435km/h (235kt), max cruising speed 378km/h (204kt). Service ceiling 22,000ft. Range with max fuel 2897km (1564nm).", "Powerplant_Desc": "C46 - Two 1495kW (2000hp) Pratt & Whitney R280034 Double Wasp piston radial engines driving three blade constant speed propellers. C46R - Two 1565kW (2100hp) Pratt & Whitney R2800 C or CA series radial pistons.", "Powerplants": "", "Production_Count": "", "Production_Status": "active", "Range_km": "", "Range_nm": "", "Record_Status": "active", "Role": "Freighter", "Seating_Config": "Flightcrew of two pilots and optional flight engineer. Typical accommodation for freight, but in an airliner configuration can seat 36, or in military configuration 50 troops.", "Service_Ceiling_ft": "", "Source_URL": "https://www.airliners.net/aircraft-data/curtiss-c46-commando/171", "Status": "In Service", "Typical_Capacity": "", "Units_Built": "3182 Commandos built for US armed forces (as the C46 for the USAAF and R5C for the USN). Many hundreds subsequently converted for civil service. Approximately 16 remain in service as of late 1998.", "WTC": "", "Weights": "C46 - Operating empty 14,970kg (33,000lb), max payload 5265kg (11,630lb), max takeoff 21,772kg (48,000lb). C46R - Empty 13,290kg (29,300lb), max takeoff 22,680kg (50,000lb).", "Wingspan_m": ""}'),
(50660, 22581, NULL, 'Global/Aircraft', 'aircraft_types.csv', '{"Aircraft_Type": "", "Bibliography": "", "Category": "3J", "Common_Name": "Douglas DC-10-30 / 40 Freighter", "Country_Origin": "", "Data_Source": "merged", "Date_Added": "2026-05-23", "Date_Modified": "2026-05-23", "Development_Story": "", "Dimensions": "", "Engine_Count": "", "Engine_Type": "", "First_Flight_Year": "", "Full_Designation": "McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30 / 40 Freighter", "Generation": "", "Height_m": "", "IATA_Code": "D1Y", "ICAO_Code": "DC10", "Length_m": "", "MTOW_kg": "", "Manufacturer": "McDonnell", "Max_Pax": "", "Max_Speed_kmh": "", "Mission_Type": "Passenger", "Model": "Douglas DC-10-30 / 40 Freighter", "Name": "", "Origin": "", "Performance": "", "Powerplant_Desc": "", "Powerplants": "", "Production_Count": "", "Production_Status": "active", "Range_km": "", "Range_nm": "", "Record_Status": "active", "Role": "", "Seating_Config": "", "Service_Ceiling_ft": "", "Source_URL": "", "Status": "In Service", "Typical_Capacity": "", "Units_Built": "", "WTC": "", "Weights": "", "Wingspan_m": ""}'),
(50661, 22581, NULL, 'Global/Aircraft', 'aircraft_types.csv', '{"Aircraft_Type": "Transcontinental range mid to large size corporate jet", "Bibliography": "Airliners.net", "Category": "2J", "Common_Name": "Falcon 2000EX/EASY/LX", "Country_Origin": "France", "Data_Source": "merged", "Date_Added": "2026-05-23", "Date_Modified": "2026-05-23", "Development_Story": "The Falcon 2000 is the latest member of the Falcon business jet line, and is a transcontinental range, slightly smaller development of the Falcon 900 trijet <p>The Falcon 2000 shares the 900''s wing and forward fuselage, but there are a number of design changes. From the start the Falcon 2000 was designed with a range of 5560km (3000nm) in mind, which is less than the transcontinental 900''s range. This design range removed the need for the redundancy of three engines for long range overwater flights, allowing the two new CFE738 engines to be fitted, which offer considerable maintenance and operating economics benefits. The CFE738 engine was developed specifically for the Falcon 2000 by a partnership of General Electric and AlliedSignal, known as CFE. Meanwhile, the 2000''s fuselage is 1.98m (6ft 6in) shorter than the 900''s and so houses less fuel, passengers and baggage. <p>Another noticeable design change between the 900 and 2000 is the area ruled rear fuselage. Dassault engineers found that the three engine layout of the 900 to be aerodynamically efficient, whereas the twin engine design of the 2000 originally would have been comparatively draggy. To combat this and reduce drag to desired levels Dassault designed an area ruled (or Coke bottle) rear fuselage, using its Catia three dimensional computer aided design program. <p>Changes to the wing include a modified leading edge and the inboard slats have been removed, while the cockpit features a Collins four screen EFIS avionics system with optional Flight Dynamics head-up displays (allowing hand flown approaches in Cat II and Cat IIIa conditions). <p>Dassault has a number of industry partners in the Falcon 2000 program, foremost of these being Alenia, which is a 25% risk sharing partner. Alenia in turn has subcontracted some work to Dee Howard and Piaggio. <p>Dassault announced it was developing the Falcon 2000, then known as the Falcon X, in June 1989. First flight occurred on March 4 1993 and certification was awarded in November 1994. The first customer delivery occurred in March 1995. <p>", "Dimensions": "Wing span 19.33m (63ft 5in), length 20.23m (66ft 5in), height 7.06m (23ft 2in). Wing area 49.0m2 (527.6sq ft).", "Engine_Count": "2", "Engine_Type": "Turbofan", "First_Flight_Year": "", "Full_Designation": "Dassault Falcon 2000EX/EASY/LX", "Generation": "", "Height_m": "", "IATA_Code": "D2L", "ICAO_Code": "F2TH", "Length_m": "20.23", "MTOW_kg": "9405", "Manufacturer": "Dassault", "Max_Pax": "", "Max_Speed_kmh": "", "Mission_Type": "Passenger", "Model": "Falcon 2000EX/EASY/LX", "Name": "Dassault Falcon 2000", "Origin": "France", "Performance": "Max cruising speed at 39,000ft Mach 0.83-0.85. Max certificated altitude 47,000ft. Range at 0.80 Mach cruising speed with eight passengers 5560km (3000nm), at 0.75 Mach 5788km (3125nm).", "Powerplant_Desc": "Two 25.6kN (5725lb) CFE (General Electric & AlliedSignal) CFE73811B turbofans.", "Powerplants": "Two 25.6kN (5725lb) CFE (General Electric & AlliedSignal) CFE73811B turbofans.", "Production_Count": "", "Production_Status": "discontinued", "Range_km": "5560", "Range_nm": "3000", "Record_Status": "active", "Role": "Transcontinental range mid to large size corporate jet", "Seating_Config": "Flightcrew of two. Main cabin seating typically for eight passengers, or up to 12 in a high density layout.", "Service_Ceiling_ft": "000", "Source_URL": "https://www.airliners.net/aircraft-data/dassault-falcon-2000/176", "Status": "In Service", "Typical_Capacity": "Flightcrew of two. Main cabin seating typically for eight passengers, or up to 12 in a high density layout.", "Units_Built": "First customer delivery occurred in March 1995. Over 60 delivered by late 1998.", "WTC": "", "Weights": "Empty equipped 9405kg (20,735lb), max takeoff 16,238kg (35,800lb).", "Wingspan_m": "19.33"}'),
