(50776, 22581, NULL, 'Global/Aircraft', 'aircraft_types.csv', '{"Aircraft_Type": "Firebomber and utility amphibian", "Bibliography": "Airliners.net", "Category": "", "Common_Name": "415", "Country_Origin": "Canada", "Data_Source": "merged", "Date_Added": "2026-05-23", "Date_Modified": "2026-05-23", "Development_Story": "The CL-215 was designed as a specialist firebomber, particularly suited to Canada and other heavily forested regions. \\n\\nThe resulting amphibious aircraft is powered by two Pratt & Whitney R-2800 radials, and is capable of scooping up 5455 litres (1200Imp gal/1440US gal) of water in 12 seconds from a water source. The CL-215 first flew on October 23 1967, and first delivery was to the French civil protection agency in June 1969. Production of batches of CL-215s continued through to 1990. \\n\\nOriginally the subsequent CL-215T was to be a simple turboprop powered development of the CL-215, and Canadair converted two aircraft in 1989 to act as development aircraft. The first of these flew on June 8 that year. Retrofit kits for CL-215s to the new standard are offered, but Canadair elected not to build new CL-215Ts, and instead developed the CL-415. \\n\\nThe primary improvement added to the CL-415 over the CL-215T is an EFIS avionics suite, while other improvements, some of which first appeared on the CL-215T, include winglets and finlets, higher weights and an increased capacity firebombing system. Like the CL-215 its principle mission is that of a firebomber, but various special mission (including SAR and maritime patrol) and transport configurations are available. \\n\\nThe first CL-415 flew in December 1993 and was delivered from April 1994. The new CL-415GR has higher operating weights.", "Dimensions": "CL-215 - Wing span 28.60m (93ft 10in), length 19.82m (65ft 1in), height 8.98m (29ft 6in). Wing area 100.3m2 (1080sq ft). CL-415 - Same except wing span over wingtips 28.63m (93ft 11in).", "Engine_Count": "", "Engine_Type": "", "First_Flight_Year": "", "Full_Designation": "Bombardier 415", "Generation": "", "Height_m": "", "IATA_Code": "", "ICAO_Code": "CL2T", "Length_m": "19.82", "MTOW_kg": "12220", "Manufacturer": "Bombardier", "Max_Pax": "", "Max_Speed_kmh": "290", "Mission_Type": "Passenger", "Model": "415", "Name": "Canadair CL-215 & 415", "Origin": "Canada", "Performance": "CL-215 - Max cruising speed 290km/h (157kt). Initial rate of climb 1000ft/min. Range at max cruising speed 1715km (925nm), at long range cruising speed 2095km (1130nm). CL-415 - Max cruising speed 376km/h (203kt), long range cruising speed 270km/h (145kt), patrol speed 240km/h (130kt). Initial rate of climb 1375ft/min. Ferry range with 500kg (1100lb) payload 2430km (1310nm).", "Powerplant_Desc": "CL-215 - Two 1565kW (2100hp) Pratt & Whitney R-2800 83AM 18 cylinder radial piston engines driving three blade constant speed propellers. CL-415 - Two 1775kW (2380shp) Pratt & Whitney Canada PW123AF turboprops driving four blade constant speed Hamilton Standard props.", "Powerplants": "CL-215 - Two 1565kW (2100hp) Pratt & Whitney R-2800 83AM 18 cylinder radial piston engines driving three blade constant speed propellers. CL-415 - Two 1775kW (2380shp) Pratt & Whitney Canada PW123AF turboprops driving four blade constant speed Hamilton Standard props.", "Production_Count": "", "Production_Status": "active", "Range_km": "1715", "Range_nm": "925", "Record_Status": "active", "Role": "Firebomber and utility amphibian", "Seating_Config": "Flightcrew of two, plus accommodation in special missions variants for a third flightdeck member, a mission specialist and two observers. Passenger configuration for 30 at 79cm (31in) pitch, or in a combi configuration for 11, with firebombing tanks retained and freight in forward fuselage. Fire retardant payload capacity of 6123kg (13,500lb).", "Service_Ceiling_ft": "1000", "Source_URL": "https://www.airliners.net/aircraft-data/canadair-cl-215-415/119", "Status": "In Service", "Typical_Capacity": "Flightcrew of two, plus accommodation in special missions variants for a third flightdeck member, a mission specialist and two observers. Passenger configuration for 30 at 79cm (31in) pitch, or in a combi configuration for 11, with firebombing tanks retained and freight in forward fuselage. Fire retardant payload capacity of 6123kg (13,500lb).", "Units_Built": "Total CL-215 production of 125. As of late 1998 51 CL-415s had been ordered.", "WTC": "", "Weights": "CL-215 firebomber - Empty 12,220kg (26,941lb), max takeoff from water 17,100kg (37,700lb), from land 19,730kg (43,500lb). CL-415 firebomber - Operating empty 12,333kg (28,353lb), max takeoff from land 19,890kg (43,850lb), from water 17,168kg (37,850lb).", "Wingspan_m": "28.60"}'),
(50777, 22581, NULL, 'Global/Aircraft', 'aircraft_types.csv', '{"Aircraft_Type": "Two seat primary and aerobatic capable trainer", "Bibliography": "Airliners.net", "Category": "", "Common_Name": "152", "Country_Origin": "United States of America", "Data_Source": "merged", "Date_Added": "2026-05-23", "Date_Modified": "2026-05-23", "Development_Story": "The introduction of the Cessna 150 marked Cessna''s return to the two seat trainer market after a six year absence and resulted in the most prolific and successful two seat trainer line in history. \\n\\nDevelopment of the original 150 began in the mid 1950s, resulting in a first flight in September 1957. This modern, all new aircraft followed the Cessna conventions then gaining favour of a strut braced high wing, all metal construction and tricycle undercarriage. Production began in September 1958. \\n\\nWhat followed was a continuous process of product improvement, although throughout the 150 model life the Continental O-200A powerplant remained unchanged. One of the most significant model changes was the 150D of 1964 which introduced the wraparound rear window. Most versions were built in Standard, Commuter and Trainer forms with differing equipment levels, while licence production was undertaken in France by Reims and in Argentina by DINFIA. Aerobat versions were stressed for limited aerobatic work. \\n\\nThe 152 was a response to availability problems with 80/87 octane fuel, and used the 150''s fuselage coupled with a Lycoming O-235 running on 100 Octane. The 152 replaced the 150 from 1977 and remained in production until late 1985. It too was progressively updated, offered in A152 Aerobat form, and also built in France.", "Dimensions": "150 - Wing span 10.17m (33ft 4in), length 6.56m (21ft 6in), height 2.11m (6ft 11in). Wing area 14.8m2 (159.5sq ft). \\n150M - Wing span 10.21m (33ft 6in), length 6.58m (21ft 7in), height 2.39m (7ft 10in). Wing area 14.6m2 (157sq ft). \\nA152 - Wing span 10.17m (33ft 4in), length 7.25m (24ft 1in), height 2.59m (8ft 6in). Wing area 14.9m2 (160sq ft).", "Engine_Count": "", "Engine_Type": "", "First_Flight_Year": "", "Full_Designation": "Cessna 152", "Generation": "", "Height_m": "", "IATA_Code": "", "ICAO_Code": "C152", "Length_m": "6.56", "MTOW_kg": "447", "Manufacturer": "Cessna", "Max_Pax": "", "Max_Speed_kmh": "200", "Mission_Type": "Passenger", "Model": "152", "Name": "Cessna 150 & 152", "Origin": "United States of America", "Performance": "150 - Max speed 200km/h (108kt), optimum cruising speed 196km/h (106kt). Initial rate of climb 640ft/min. Service ceiling 15,300ft. Range 563km (304nm). \\n150M - Max speed 201km/h (109kt), max cruising speed 196km/h (106kt), economical cruising speed 159km/h (86kt). Initial rate of climb 670ft/min. Service ceiling 12,250ft. Max range with no reserves 909km (490nm), or 1424km (769nm) with optional fuel.\\nA152 - Max speed 200km/h (108kt), cruising speed 195km/h (105kt). Initial rate of climb 715ft/min. Range 575km (310nm).", "Powerplant_Desc": "150 - One 75kW (100hp) Continental O-200A flat four piston engine driving a two blade fixed pitch prop. \\nA152 Aerobat - One 80kW (108hp) Lycoming O-235-N2C.", "Powerplants": "150 - One 75kW (100hp) Continental O-200A flat four piston engine driving a two blade fixed pitch prop. \\nA152 Aerobat - One 80kW (108hp) Lycoming O-235-N2C.", "Production_Count": "", "Production_Status": "active", "Range_km": "563", "Range_nm": "304", "Record_Status": "active", "Role": "Two seat primary and aerobatic capable trainer", "Seating_Config": "Typical seating for two side by side.", "Service_Ceiling_ft": "640", "Source_URL": "https://www.airliners.net/aircraft-data/cessna-150-152/138", "Status": "In Service", "Typical_Capacity": "Typical seating for two side by side.", "Units_Built": "Total 150 and 152 production amounts to 31,289 aircraft over 27 years, comprising 6860 US built 152s, 589 French built 152s, 22,082 US built 150s and 1758 French built 150s, and 39 Argentinian built A-150s.", "WTC": "", "Weights": "150 - Empty 447kg (985lb), max takeoff 681kg (1500lb). \\n150M - Empty 458kg (1010lb), max takeoff 726kg (1600lb). \\nA152 - Empty 513kg (1131lb), max takeoff 760kg (1675lb).", "Wingspan_m": "10.17"}'),
